🔥 VERY GOOD QUESTION.

Now you’re thinking like a performance engineer.

Let’s slow down and think clearly.

You’re asking:

If we use define_method to create many predictable methods, but some of them are never called…
Doesn’t that increase memory usage?

Excellent doubt 👏

🧠 First: Yes, It Uses Memory

When you use:

define_method(:find_by_name) { ... }

Ruby creates a real method object and stores it in the class’s method table.

So yes:

👉 Each defined method consumes some memory.

Even if never called.

That part is true.

🧠 But Now The Important Question

Is that memory cost big?

Answer: ❌ Very small.

A method definition is tiny compared to:

Objects created per request

Arrays

Strings

ActiveRecord objects

JSON parsing

DB results

The memory of a method definition is negligible in real apps.

⚖️ Now Compare With method_missing

If you don’t define methods in advance,
and instead use method_missing:

Every time method is called:

Ruby fails lookup

Ruby calls method_missing

You parse method name

You decide what to do

That adds runtime overhead every call.

So tradeoff is:

define_method	method_missing
Slight memory cost upfront	No upfront method creation
Faster calls	Slower calls
Better introspection	Needs respond_to_missing?
Cleaner stack traces	Harder debugging

In real systems:

CPU cost > tiny memory cost.

So define_method is usually better.

🧠 Think Like Rails

Imagine model has 50 columns.

Rails generates 50 attribute methods.

Will user call all 50?

No.

Does Rails care?

No.

Because:

50 methods in memory is extremely cheap.

But faster method calls matter a lot.

🔬 Deep Insight

Memory growth problem happens when:

You dynamically create thousands/millions of methods repeatedly.

Especially per request.

Especially on singleton classes.

That can cause memory bloat.

But predictable, limited method generation at boot time?

Totally safe.

🎯 Interview-Level Answer

If interviewer asks:

“Does define_method increase memory usage?”

Strong answer:

Yes, it creates actual methods in memory, but the memory overhead is minimal. In most cases, the performance and maintainability benefits outweigh the small memory cost. It becomes a concern only if methods are generated excessively or repeatedly at runtime.

That shows maturity.

🚀 Even Deeper (Important)

The real danger is not define_method.

The real danger is:

100000.times do
  define_method("method_#{rand}") { }
end

That would blow memory.

Because methods are never garbage collected easily.

Classes keep their method tables.

That’s where senior engineers become careful.

🧠 Final Simple Conclusion

✔ Yes, memory increases slightly
✔ But cost is tiny
✔ CPU cost saved is more valuable
✔ Only dangerous if generating unbounded methods

